"/> Now, this is going to sound like there's some Antique Market Code, but
it's really just a summary of what's usual around here.

The &quot;rules&quot; generally are that if you pick something up you have a
reasonable time to examine it without someone else horning in with an
offering to buy it. There are limits. You really can't expect to lay
claim to everything in sight with a simple mention that you're &quot;thinking
about it&quot;. You can't set it back down and step away and preserve any
claim to it by saying you'll probably take it but want to think about
it. Around here, if you set it down without a clear statement that
you'll take it, it's up for grabs. If you really want it, you had better
say so, have a hand on it, or have it in arms.

You may, if the dealer's agreeable, say you believe you want that and
that and that if you can inspect them each in turn first, if you don't
mess around too long.

You can't step in while another buyer has something in hand, ask the
price, and offer more, nor can you break into negotiations with an offer
to pay the asking price. It's not an auction. You can, though, if you
think there may be more people interested than you and the first
prospective buyer, lay a sort of secondary claim by announcing that you
will make an offer if the first customer decides against it.

This isn't comment on the related tale. Wasn't there. Didn't see it.
Can't tell if &quot;collector&quot; means a focused collector or just a non-dealer
buyer. In the final analysis, the seller makes the &quot;rules&quot;, even if the
rules don't conform to the usual for that venue. In this case, the
dealer seems to have come down firmly on one side.

At the moment, I happen to have quite a warm feeling for collectors,
particularly collectors of antique lawn sprinklers with deep pockets.
