Let's say I have a property for sale. A person expresses a keen interest
and has her agent write up a full-price offer. She writes a check for
3% of the purchase price BUT instructs her agent to hold both the offer
and earnest money check until she can get opinions from several relatives.

Does this person have my property in her &quot;shopping cart&quot;? She may
believe she does, but she has no legal rights vis a vis my property.
I can sell it in the next five minutes to someone offering less than full
price, full price or 145,000 quatloos, if I so desire.

In other words, &quot;dibs&quot; is not a meaningful legal concept if there is
no consideration given. And I don't see any difference if the property
is real estate or a Tiffany mixed metals piece from the Aesthetic period.

The original poster was saying, in effect, &quot;Go away. I've got first
dibs.&quot; Juvenile rules of conduct like &quot;dibs&quot; work fine when everyone
